 from the broadcast schedule at the end of the 20th century, but promoters of social media and television services still kept audiences under control, replacing the schedule with surveillance of media use. Author Randall Patnode offers compelling new insights into the intermingled roles of broadcasting and industrial/post-industrial work and how Americans spend their time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aInternetxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision viewerszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  atv, broadcasting, media, media studies, communication, live tv, synchronized, asynchronous, synchronous.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079130340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978820135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978820135/original  a978-3-11-079130-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK